{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.53,0.11,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27222"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner following a positive urine pregnancy test and a missed period six weeks ago. Her obstetric history includes a previous medical termination at seven weeks, a miscarriage at 12 weeks, a stillbirth at 24 weeks and one vaginal birth plus a set of twins delivered via Caesarean section. She has three children at home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer general practitioner wishes to simplify the documentation of her obstetric history by recording her gravidity and parity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In the assumption she is currently pregnant, which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["G6P2+1-1","G6P3+1-1","G7P4-1","G7P3+1","G6P5+1-1"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had quite a tumultuous reproductive journey, but in total has become pregnant six times including her current pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETermination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMiscarriage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStillbirth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESingleton\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis makes her gravidity 6.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParity refers to the number of pregnancies that have extended beyond 20 weeks, and in her case this has occurs three times.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStillbirth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESingleton\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite there being two babies in a set of twins, this is still counted as one pregnancy and therefore her parity is 3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stillbirth is recorded as 1-1\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe twin birth is recored as 1+1\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherefore, her gravidity and parity can be denoted as G6P3+1-1\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gravidity refers to the number of times a woman has been pregnant","Parity refers to the number of pregnancies that have made it until 20 weeks","Stillbirth refers to death before delivery of a fetus \u003E20 weeks or 400grams","Miscarriage refers to involuntary pregnancy loss prior to 20 weeks gestation"],"references":["Australian Institute of Health and Welfare. Stillbirths and neonatal deaths [Internet]. Canberra: Australian Institute of Health and Welfare, 2021 Available from: https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/mothers-babies/stillbirths-and-neonatal-deaths","Symonds IM, Arulkumaran S. Essential obstetrics and gynaecology. Edinburgh: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27222"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27222"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-03T09:16:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-14T08:46:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4469"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading